k- <a href=\"http://www.trentu.ca/admin/specialneeds/learninginnovations/thinkingandlearning/public/Unit13%20-%20Sleep%20and%20Learning%20Handout.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fdd630f72eef3790bfb4ef38d08c7f85?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/166/konrad-rudolph","reputation":3847,"display_name":"Konrad Rudolph"},"score":2,"post_id":326,"edited":false,"creation_date":1325248973,"comment_id":406,"body":"@Innab It\u2019s irrelevant that the energy expense is only a fraction. The important thing is that there is any at all. Do the math, it will <i>never<\/i> be beneficial to rest instead spending the same time hunting, because the net energy balance of hunting is <i>positive<\/i> (i.e. energy take-in rather than expense), so in sum, resting will always spend more energy than hunting."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"score":5,"post_id":326,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fdd630f72eef3790bfb4ef38d08c7f85?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/166/konrad-rudolph","reputation":3847,"display_name":"Konrad Rudolph"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1327839373,"comment_id":957,"body":"@KonradRudolph surely that is only the case if the hunt is successful - therefore sleeping can be <i>less disadvantageous<\/i> in terms of energy expenditure if the odds are heavily stacked against successful predation at a certain time of day."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/F4aa0.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6380,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6380/bunk","reputation":873,"display_name":"Bunk"},"score":1,"post_id":326,"edited":false,"creation_date":1410367065,"comment_id":33242,"body":"#2 also doesn&#39;t apply to nocturnal animals; especially animals that are active at different times of the day specifically to avoid predators."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1324748976,"creation_date":1324748976,"body":"<p>From what I've learned, there are two theories to answer that question:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>Restoration - the body needs to rest in order to renew its metabolism (if an animal is active 24/7, it will constantly use up a lot energy and metabolism). It has been shown that mice that have gone a while without sleeping have a compromised immune system.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Preservation - sleep is assumed to confer a survival advantage. Night time is a dangerous time, so sleep sort of 'forces' an animal to lay low for a few hours.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":326,"question_id":324,"up_vote_count":8},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"score":23,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/49e94b363348f897f337a5bce2beec20?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":68,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/68/marta-cz-c","reputation":1717,"display_name":"Marta Cz-C","accept_rate":50},"score":2,"post_id":843,"edited":false,"creation_date":1327845111,"comment_id":958,"body":"So is it just a coincidence that the metabolic pathway of glycogen synthesis in brain evolved to be regulated by neurotransmitters? If it had evolved independently - we wouldn&#39;t need any sleep?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"score":1,"post_id":843,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/49e94b363348f897f337a5bce2beec20?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":68,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/68/marta-cz-c","reputation":1717,"display_name":"Marta Cz-C","accept_rate":50},"edited":false,"creation_date":1327872152,"comment_id":965,"body":"@MartaCz-C that&#39;s a really good point, and if I&#39;m honest I&#39;ve struggled to find an answer in literature for you.  However it could be said that as the glycogen reserves are in essence a backup power supply, even if neurotransmitters were not involved such a supply is not likely to be replenished without a greatly reduced energy demand (i.e. in sleep) as otherwise any glucose that arrived would be quickly used rather than stored in glycogenesis.  It could be an adaption rather than a co-incidence if this is the case - forcing an organism to take a period of rest to rebuild these supplies."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1327841762,"creation_date":1327841762,"body":"<p>I found <a href=\"http://web.sbu.edu/biology/Benington/Prog%20Neurobiol%2045347.pdf\">this paper by Benington and Heller<\/a> that expands on the previously mentioned theory of sleep as a mechanism to renew metabolism.  They hypothesise that sleep is necessary to replenish glycogen stores (mainly within astrocytes) in the brain.  These stores are normally used to supplement blood glucose due to the high energy demands of the brain.  <\/p>\n\n<p>It is suggested that this may also result in the manifestation of feeling sleepy as a consequence of the exhaustion of glycogen supplies in specific small areas of the brain.  Brief and localised depletion of glycogen stores mean that cells are operating with less energy than they normally have to work with.  This causes an increase in synthesis of adenosine from the breakdown of AMP.  The paper maintains that the increased levels of adenosine are detected by adenosine receptors which then triggers or increases (as seen on EEG scans) the feeling of the need for sleep:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/jF4cA.jpg\" alt=\"Flowchart of the relation of glycogen to sleep need and replenishment\"><\/p>\n\n<p>In NREM sleep (which may lend some support to the theory as NREM sleep accounts for 80% of sleep and is most physiologically different to waking), this glycogen is most efficiently replaced.  During NREM sleep the release of glycogenolysis inducing neurotransmitters is reduced, allowing glycogen-synthase to predominate and glycogen levels to be restored.  However, these same neurotransmitters are key in the processing sensory stimuli (by tonically depolarising neurons in the sensory cortex).  <strong>Therefore glycogen replenishment will always be associated with a (strongly) reduced response to stimuli<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p>This leads to finally answering the question as to why sleep has an evolutionary advantage, which I will quote verbatim to maintain the authors momentum:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Glycogen replenishment during waking would be maladaptive because it would impair the organism's ability to to process and respond to sensory stimuli.  <strong>Sleep has therefore evolved as a state where animals retreat to a safe environment, behaviour is suppressed and glycogen stores are replenished<\/strong>. <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":843,"question_id":324,"up_vote_count":23}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/324/why-did-the-process-of-sleep-evolve-in-many-animals-what-is-its-evolutionary-ad","last_activity_date":1327841762,"creation_date":1324739450,"answer_count":3,"title":"Why did the process of sleep evolve in many animals? What is its evolutionary advantage?","body":"<p>The process of sleep seems to be very disadvantageous to an organism as it is extremely vulnerable to predation for several hours at a time. Why is sleep necessary in so many animals? What advantage did it give the individuals that evolved to have it as an adaptation? When and how did it likely occur in the evolutionary path of animals?<\/p>\n","question_id":324,"tags":["evolution","sleep"],"score":66,"down_vote_count":0,"protected_date":1423818790,"is_answered":true,"view_count":3885,"up_vote_count":66,"last_edit_date":1325012810},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dc032d9988e993a4c4b99bbaff48ddaa?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":263,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/263/mring","reputation":888,"display_name":"mring","accept_rate":94},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550aa98332616362fa07d023da45d40?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":28,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/28/gergana-vandova","reputation":5081,"display_name":"Gergana Vandova","accept_rate":35},"score":2,"post_id":824,"edited":false,"creation_date":1327613199,"comment_id":943,"body":"are you familiar with concepts like haploid, homozygos, alleles, chrossing over? I am trying to figure out how high scientific level my answer should be."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6ec38796d74b8247ad51465641599a0c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":397,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/397/stoicfury","reputation":534,"display_name":"stoicfury"},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1327684795,"creation_date":1327612147,"body":"<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meiosis\" rel=\"nofollow\">Meiosis<\/a> is the type of cell division responsible for the diversification of genetic material among egg and sperm cells. The diversity comes primarily from <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromosomal_crossover\" rel=\"nofollow\">crossing over<\/a> (<em>Prophase I<\/em>) and the cell divisions (<em>Telophase I &amp; II<\/em>) later on in the process.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Meiosis begins with <strong>one diploid cell<\/strong> containing two copies of each\n  chromosome\u2014one from the organism's mother and one from its father\u2014and\n  <strong>produces four haploid cells<\/strong> containing one copy of each chromosome.\n  Each of <strong>the resulting chromosomes in the gamete cells is a unique\n  mixture of maternal and paternal DNA<\/strong>, ensuring that offspring are\n  genetically distinct from either parent. This gives rise to genetic\n  diversity in sexually reproducing populations, which provides the\n  variation of physical and behavioural attributes (phenotypes) upon\n  which natural selection acts.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Further detail of the precise phases can be found in <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meiosis#Phases\" rel=\"nofollow\">the Wikipeida article<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/12lFp.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/12lFp.jpg\" alt=\"meiosis\"><\/a>\n<sub>[picture from <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meiosis\" rel=\"nofollow\">wikipedia]<\/a><\/sub><\/p>\n","answer_id":827,"question_id":824,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1327684795},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/55b2cca3b7a11df3a961d57a68705503?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":43,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/43/daniel-standage","reputation":3502,"display_name":"Daniel Standage","accept_rate":76},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1327612294,"creation_date":1327612294,"body":"<p>I think we can attribute this to sheer probability. The human genome contains around 3 billion base pairs. When you consider recombination from chromosomal crossover that occurs in germ line cells, there is an astronomically huge number of possible unique combinations that can be made.<\/p>\n\n<p>Of course, males generate many many sperm, so some of these are bound to be similar. But the number of sperm produced by any individual doesn't come anywhere close to the number of possible unique sperm that he could produce.<\/p>\n","answer_id":828,"question_id":824,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/824/how-are-the-gene-sequences-of-individual-sperm-and-egg-cells-randomized","last_activity_date":1327684795,"creation_date":1327601530,"answer_count":2,"title":"How are the gene sequences of individual sperm and egg cells \"randomized\"?","body":"<p>What I mean by \"randomized\" is, in the place where an egg cell or sperm cell is made, what is the mechanism by which each one is not made identically? Though I am a layman, I'm pretty sure that if the sperm cell that was right next to \"me\" had made it to the egg instead of the one that did, the resultant human would have a different genomic sequence and different features.<\/p>\n","question_id":824,"tags":["human-biology","physiology","reproduction","human-genetics"],"score":6,"accepted_answer_id":827,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":711,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550aa98332616362fa07d023da45d40?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":28,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/28/gergana-vandova","reputation":5081,"display_name":"Gergana Vandova","accept_rate":35},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f14b385134cf5b6a0f3e1695bc63cd23?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":48,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/48/aleadam","reputation":1788,"display_name":"Aleadam"},"score":6,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"score":2,"post_id":743,"edited":false,"creation_date":1327136111,"comme