lemaniac finding answers yourself is absolutely fine =D  It might be a better idea to post them <i>as answers<\/i> rather than editing them into your question though, as this may be clearer to future people who may find this question by google for example."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6b2790c74560690d1a476d9ee079a50b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":352,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/352/qazwsx","reputation":290,"display_name":"qazwsx","accept_rate":75},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1326669233,"creation_date":1326665596,"body":"<p>The plants are called <strong>Biennial plants<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Examples would be <strong>carrots<\/strong> or <strong>dandelions<\/strong>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":674,"question_id":655,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1326669233}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/655/which-plants-live-for-more-than-one-year-and-less-than-two-years","last_activity_date":1326669264,"creation_date":1326580220,"answer_count":1,"title":"Which plants live for more than one year and less than two years?","body":"<p>What kinds of plants live for more than one year and less than two years? Are there any categorical or taxonomical names for such plants?<\/p>\n","question_id":655,"tags":["botany","taxonomy"],"score":-2,"accepted_answer_id":674,"down_vote_count":5,"closed_reason":"too localized","is_answered":true,"view_count":717,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1326669264},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f115740b8a3b86d0b3fc50ef02c06766?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":277,"link":"http: