uting to increased volume<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":480,"question_id":475,"up_vote_count":8}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/475/why-does-regular-exercise-increase-brain-volume","last_activity_date":1325737096,"creation_date":1325714259,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why does regular exercise increase brain volume?","body":"<p>It has been shown in several studies that regular aerobic exercise increases brain volume in aging humans. The changes were observed in hippocampus and were correlated with dramatic reduction of age-related dementia. Interestingly, the intensity of training had little influence on the results: walking, climbing stairs, gardening were just as effective at reducing dementia as more strenuous exercise.<\/p>\n\n<p>What is the biological mechanism behind this phenomena?<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/IS0pr.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Fig. The aerobic exercise group showed an increase in the anterior hippocampus and no change in the posterior hippocampus.[<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/IS0pr.jpg\">1<\/a>]<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Erickson et al. <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21282661\">Exercise training increases size of hippocampus and improves memory<\/a>. PNAS. 2011. <\/li>\n<li>Colcombe et al. <a href=\"http://biomedgerontology.oxfordjournals.org/content/61/11/1166.abstract\">Aerobic exercise training increases brain volume in aging humans<\/a>. J Gerontology. 2006<\/li>\n<li>Ravaglia, et al. <a href=\"http://www.neurology.org/content/70/19_Part_2/1786.abstract\">Physical activity and dementia risk in the elderly<\/a>. Neurology. 2008<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","question_id":475,"tags":["neuroscience","neuroanatomy","senescence"],"score":18,"accepted_answer_id":480,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":525,"up_vote_count":18},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user24"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ab24