ytalky","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":414,"edited":false,"creation_date":1325545081,"comment_id":457,"body":"@Tim In which case you probably need to be more specific about the experiment you&#39;re proposing. Your question seems to boil down to how fully the H-H model describes the behaviour of an actual axon membrane propagating APs. (There&#39;s an auxiliary issue of how well your sim implements the model, but let&#39;s shelve that for now.) Not having done the experiment, I can only guess. My intuition is that it would be possible to drive a real membrane to steady state if you&#39;re sufficiently aggressive about it, but that doing so would not demonstrate anything meaningful."},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user24"},"score":0,"post_id":414,"edited":false,"creation_date":1325545347,"comment_id":458,"body":"The question is rather how well the model describes reality in one specific aspect. A way to check would be to clamp a squid giant axon the way Hodgkin and Huxley did, apply a constant current of sufficient amplitude, and measure the membrane potential."},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user24"},"score":0,"post_id":414,"edited":false,"creation_date":1325545472,"comment_id":459,"body":"I don&#39;t find it improbable that this could be a known problem with the model or a known behaviour of the real membrane."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3321e3f5894bfc21bb2c07f645181187?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":149,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/149/walkytalky","reputation":508,"display_name":"walkytalky","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":414,"edited":false,"creation_date":1325545801,"comment_id":460,"body":"@Tim For that experiment, I broadly stand by my guess. With sufficient current injection you could overwhelm the oscillatory behaviours of the channel population. It would, however, be interesting to see how closely the real current n