es your question to a truism if applied to mass extinctions - if only small animals remain then non-directional evolution would give the impression of progression."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1e2e8e9b67646db490fc27d32e015805?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":18,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18/alanse","reputation":186,"display_name":"AlanSE"},"score":0,"post_id":111,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d5e8817011bf40f20c518af3c0dc7187?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":137,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/137/kennypeanuts","reputation":1522,"display_name":"KennyPeanuts","accept_rate":75},"edited":false,"creation_date":1323987006,"comment_id":122,"body":"@DQdlM Is it common that an animal species decreases in size then differentiates into many other species?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d5e8817011bf40f20c518af3c0dc7187?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":137,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/137/kennypeanuts","reputation":1522,"display_name":"KennyPeanuts","accept_rate":75},"score":0,"post_id":111,"edited":false,"creation_date":1323999170,"comment_id":147,"body":"@Zassounotsukushi I don&#39;t think there is much support for those kinds of generalizations.  Different ecological contexts would tend to apply selection pressure for body size in different ways and those ecological contexts will vary in space and time.  As Kevin points out in his answer the potential for large changes in body size have been shown so it is a plastic trait but it will respond to the selection pressures at hand (as Nick T points out in his comment on island dwarfism)."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":107,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/107/kmm","reputation":8486,"display_name":"kmm"},"score":22,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1323982204,"comment_id":114,"body":"i&#39;d heard that miniaturization of animals is also a recognized effect of subpopulations on islands.  gigantism can also occur, but is the result of the organism differentiating into new niches.  the hobbits are examples of this effect, do i remember right?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":107,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/107/kmm","reputation":8486,"display_name":"kmm"},"score":0,"post_id":114,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"edited":false,"creation_date":1323987436,"comment_id":123,"body":"It probably goes equally both ways. Examples of miniturization are balanced by examples of gigantism (e.g., lots of South American taxa during its &quot;island&quot; period)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":114,"edited":false,"creation_date":1326735327,"comment_id":713,"body":"yes - i think its a matter of niches being open for just a few critters to fit into and sizes can change drastically. in crowded systems, the time it takes to change size would be prohibitive."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1323972989,"creation_date":1323972989,"body":"<p>Your question brings up several important issues with regards to the evolution of body size. The rationale for concluding that the ancestral mammal had a small body size is that all of the taxa in that area of the tree tend to be small. In contrast, if all of those taxa had been cow-sized, then the most parsimonious conclusion would be that the ancestral mammal was cow-sized.<\/p>\n\n<h2>Identification of ancestors is difficult<\/h2>\n\n<p>Identification of a fossil species as <em>the most recent common ancestor<\/em> of a pair of sister taxa is exceedingly difficult. The way that different species are diagnosed in fossils in by their unique derived characteristics (<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autapomorphy\">autapomorphies<\/a>). So if a fossil is found with no autapomorphies, then it is plausibly an ancestor (i.e., at the split between two sister taxa). Some would argue that if you don't find any autapomorphies, then you just haven't looked closely enough.<\/p>\n\n<h2>Cope's Rule<\/h2>\n\n<p>The idea that lineages tend to evolve toward larger body size is known as <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cope%27s_rule\">Cope's Rule<\/a>, named for the paleontologist Edward Drinker Cope. The success of Cope's Rule has been highly variable, with some lineages following and others not (<a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/2897758\">Polly, 1998<\/a>). <\/p>\n\n<p>Some clades following Cope's Rule<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Early reptiliomorphs (<a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/10635150490445706\">Laurin, 2004<\/a>)<\/li>\n<li>Pterodactyloidea (<a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1420-9101.2006.01284.x/abstract\">Hone and Benton, 2007<\/a>)<\/li>\n<li>Most Cambrian-Devonian marine invertebrates (<a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1666/0094-8373%282008%29034%5B0210%3aEBTICM%5D2.0.CO;2\">Novack-Gottshall, 2008<\/a>)<\/li>\n<li>North American canids (<a href=\"http://www.sciencemag.org/content/306/5693/101.short\">Van Valkenburgh et al., 2004<\/a>)<\/li>\n<li>Mesozoic birds (<a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1420-9101.2007.01483.x/full\">Hone et al., 2008<\/a>)<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Some clades not following Cope's Rule<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Early stegocephalians (<a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/10635150490445706\">Laurin, 2004<\/a>)<\/li>\n<li>\"Rhamphorhynchoid\" pterosaurs (<a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1420-9101.2006.01284.x/abstract\">Hone and Benton, 2007<\/a>)<\/li>\n<li>Mesozoic birds (<a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1420-9101.2008.01594.x/full\">Butler and Goswami, 2008<\/a>)<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Note that many results depend on the methods used.<\/p>\n\n<h2>Evidence from experimental evolution<\/h2>\n\n<p>Several studies have addressed body size evolution in vertebrates both directly and indirectly. MacArthur (<a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/10.2307/2457976\">1944a<\/a>, <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/stable/10.2307/2458253\">1944b<\/a>) directly selected for large and small body mass in laboratory mice. Within 8 generations, mean body masses had increased or decreased by over 50%. Even when body mass is not directly selected upon, mass can change in a correlated way. <a href=\"http://www.biology.ucr.edu/people/faculty/Garland.html\">Selection for high levels of voluntary activity<\/a> has led to an approximately 25% reduction in body mass.<\/p>\n\n<p>Based on these studies, evolution of body size (larger or smaller) is certainly possible within relatively few generations.<\/p>\n","answer_id":114,"question_id":111,"up_vote_count":22}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/111/do-large-animals-often-evolve-into-smaller-animals","last_activity_date":1323972989,"creation_date":1323970079,"answer_count":1,"title":"Do large animals often evolve into smaller animals?","body":"<p>There are several examples where the largest animals were killed off preferentially due to a major ecological shift:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>The KT extinction event<\/li>\n<li>The Holocene extinction, as well as the major megafauna humans killed off<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mammaliaformes\">common ancestor of modern mammals<\/a> is thought to be \"shrew-like\" in size, and it differentiated into most of the large animal species in the world today.  I imagine that a similar statement can be made for dinosaurs.  In general it seems that a major extinction event is likely to be best weathered by smaller creatures which can later, over time, increase in size to fill the niche that larger animals, and evolution dictates it will be profitable to do so.<\/p>\n\n<p>Does this limit large animals to only the branches of the tree of life?  Any given set of (Multicellular) species obviously share a common ancestor that is much smaller than them.  Is it possible for many species to share a common ancestor that is considerably larger than any of them?<\/p>\n","question_id":111,"tags":["evolution","zoology"],"score":16,"accepted_answer_id":114,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":929,"up_vote_count":17,"last_edit_date":1323971664},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user132"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1059206e9cdfa0201e2f13d43181c730?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":66,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/66/alexander-galkin","reputation":5247,"display_name":"Alexander Galkin"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user132"},"score":2,"post_id":85,"edited":false,"creation_date":1323957369,"comment_id":67,"body":"Beautiful. Now, what were these &quot;molecular findings&quot; that were instrumental in collating all those <i>Salmonella<\/i> &quot;species&