\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":85,"question_id":82,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a71658d81f8a82a8122050f21bb86d3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":25,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/25/nick-t","reputation":1720,"display_name":"Nick T","accept_rate":75},"score":15,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user132"},"score":0,"post_id":88,"edited":false,"creation_date":1323957532,"comment_id":68,"body":"Nice survey article! (Even the switch from <i>choleraesuis<\/i> to <i>enterica<\/i> is discussed.) Thanks for this. I believe you intended &quot;<i>typhosa<\/i>&quot; instead of &quot;<i>thphosa<\/i>&quot;, though."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a71658d81f8a82a8122050f21bb86d3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":25,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/25/nick-t","reputation":1720,"display_name":"Nick T","accept_rate":75},"score":0,"post_id":88,"edited":false,"creation_date":1323957622,"comment_id":69,"body":"@J.M. probably...it&#39;s misspelled in the review though <code>:&#47;<\/code>"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1323957603,"creation_date":1323957213,"body":"<p>Simply put, old habits die hard; physicians and other medical personnel have grown up with the old species designations so will continue to use them.  This is somewhat the reverse of the case with <em>E. coli<\/em>, where <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2974192/?tool=pmcentrez\">80-90% of the genome is variable<\/a> across strains.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17760271\">Lin-Hui gives a brief history<\/a>, where strains identified early were given specific names within <em>Salmonella<\/em> like <em>typhi<\/em>, <em>typhimurium<\/em>, <em>panama<\/em>, etc.  In 1966 it was proposed to lump serovars together among three species <em>S.\ncholeraesuis<\/em>, <em>S. typhosa<\/em>, and <em>S. kauffmannii<\/em>.  Shortly thereafter in 1972 with the advent of DNA techniques, it was shown they really should be all piled together.  There is one exception, <em>Salmonella choleraesuis subsp. bongori<\/em>, separated in 1989.<\/p>\n","answer_id":88,"question_id":82,"up_vote_count":15,"last_edit_date":1323957603}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/82/why-is-there-now-only-one-salmonella-species","last_activity_date":1323960446,"creation_date":1323955733,"answer_count":2,"title":"Why is there now only one Salmonella species?","body":"<p>Once upon a time, I chanced upon an old microbiology book that detailed the rather colorful world of enterobacteria. <em>Salmonella<\/em> in particular stood out, as it seemed there were a lot of species: <em>typhi<\/em> / <em>typhosa<\/em>, <em>paratyphi<\/em>, <em>gallinarum<\/em>, <em>typhimurium<\/em>, <em>choleraesuis<\/em>, and quite a bunch of others that I have now forgotten.<\/p>\n\n<p>Flipping through a newer book, it now seems that all of these \"species\" were collated under <em>choleraesuis<\/em> (and now more recently <em>enterica<\/em>), with all those species being demoted to \"strains\" (or maybe I should use the current term of art, \"serovar\"). Unfortunately, the book didn't give much in the way of explaining about this merger.<\/p>\n\n<p>So, why is there now only <em>S. enterica<\/em>? If \"<em>S. typhi<\/em>\" is a mere serovar, how come the species name is still used in the literature?<\/p>\n","question_id":82,"tags":["microbiology","history","bacteriology"],"score":16,"accepted_answer_id":88,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":266,"up_vote_count":16,"last_edit_date":1323960446},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/530fba2575c8d41e71a78e994d8f6e43?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":128,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/128/pedery","reputation":153,"display_name":"Pedery"},"comments":[{"ow